05578nam a22008175i 9780691250687DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912506877 a10.1515/97806912506872doi  a(DE-B1597)651555  a(OCoLC)1396907964  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aJC574 7aPOL0420202bisacsh04a320.5109223/eng/202301111 aKahan, Alan S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFreedom from Fear :bAn Incomplete History of Liberalism /cAlan S. Kahan. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (528 p.) :b2 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPart I: Prologue -- t1 Liberalism -- t2 Before the Revolutions -- tPart II: The All-Too-Short Nineteenth Century -- t3 After the Revolutions -- t4 Many-Splendored Liberalism -- t5 Liberalism on the Front Lines: Freedom, Nation, God -- t6 Liberalisms with Something Missing -- tPart III: New Fears, New Hopes -- t7 Modern Liberalism versus Classical Liberalism -- t8 Liberalism’s Limits -- t9 A World in Crisis and the Crisis of Liberalism, 1919–1945 -- t10 Hollow Victories, 1945–2000 -- t11 Liberalism and Populism: The Search for a Solution -- tAppendix -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex -- tA Note On The Type0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA provocative new history of liberalism that also provides a roadmap for today’s liberalsFreedom from Fear offers a striking new account of the dominant political and social theory of our time: liberalism. In a pathbreaking reframing of the historical debate, Alan Kahan charts the development of Western liberalism from the late eighteenth century to the present. Examining key liberal thinkers and issues, Kahan shows how liberalism is both a response to fear and a source of hope: the search for a world in which no one need be afraid.Freedom from Fear reveals how liberal arguments typically rely on three pillars: freedom, markets, and morals. But when liberals ignore one or more of these pillars, their arguments generally fail to persuade. Extending from Adam Smith and Montesquieu to today’s battles between liberals and populists, the book examines the twists and turns of the “incomplete” or unfinished liberal tradition while demonstrating its fundamental continuity. It combines fresh accounts of familiar figures such as Tocqueville and Rawls with discussions of less-famous but pivotal thinkers such as A. V. Dicey and Jane Addams, and explores how liberals have dealt with crucial issues, from debates over male and female suffrage to colonialism and liberal anti-Catholicism.By transforming our understanding of the history of liberal thought and practice, Freedom from Fear provides a new picture of the political creed today: the paths liberals need to follow, the questions they need to answer, and the dead ends they must avoid—if they are to win.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLiberalismxHistory. 0aState, The. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Conservatism & Liberalism.2bisacsh  aA. V. Dicey.  aBastiat.  aBenjamin Constant.  aHayek.  aJ. S. Mill.  aJames Madison.  aJane Addams Adam Smith.  aJohn Rawls.  aLiberalism.  aMontesquieu.  aNozick.  aTocqueville.  aclassical liberalism.  ahistory of political thought.  aintellectual history.  apolitical theory: libertarianism.  apopulism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Polit